{"title_page": "Lateral flow test", "text_new": "{{Context|date=October 2009}}\n[[File:Lateral Flow Assay.jpg|thumb|499x499px|A NASA illustration of a lateral flow assay.[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Lateral_Flow_Assay.jpg#filehistory]]]\n'''Lateral flow tests''',<ref>[http://www.ivdtechnology.com/article/concurrent-engineering-lateral-flow-diagnostics Concurrent Engineering for Lateral-Flow Diagnostics (IVDT archive, Nov 99)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415073429/http://www.ivdtechnology.com/article/concurrent-engineering-lateral-flow-diagnostics |date=2014-04-15 }}</ref> also known as '''lateral flow [[immunoaffinity chromatography|immunochromatographic]] assays''', are simple cellulose-based devices intended to detect the presence of a target [[Analyte|analyte]] in liquid sample without the need for specialized and costly equipment, though many lab-based applications enhance their usage by employing dedicated equipment for higher sensitivity readout.<ref name=\"Yetisen2013\">{{cite journal | author = Yetisen A. K. | year = 2013 | title = Paper-based microfluidic point-of-care diagnostic devices | journal = Lab on a Chip |volume= 13 |issue= 12 |pages= 2210\u20132251 |doi=10.1039/C3LC50169H| pmid = 23652632 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/dbe9e0546e94ccba6732679cfbe080f81e6415ca }}</ref> Lateral flow tests operate on the same principles as the enzyme-linked immunosorbent assays ([[ELISA]]). In essence, these tests run a liquid along the surface of a pad with reactive molecules that show a visual positive or negative result. Typically, these tests are used for medical diagnostics for home testing, point of care testing, or laboratory use. The home pregnancy test is a known and widely used application. These tests are simple, economic and generally show results in around 5-30 minutes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koczula|first=Katarzyna\u00a0M.|last2=Gallotta|first2=Andrea|date=2016-06-30|title=Lateral flow assays|journal=Essays in Biochemistry|volume=60|issue=1|pages=111\u2013120|doi=10.1042/EBC20150012|issn=0071-1365|pmc=4986465|pmid=27365041}}</ref> Lateral flow tests have recently seen use in diagnosing ebola<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kaushik|first=Ajeet|last2=Tiwari|first2=Sneham|last3=Dev Jayant|first3=Rahul|last4=Marty|first4=Aileen|last5=Nair|first5=Madhavan|date=2016-01-15|title=Towards detection and diagnosis of Ebola virus disease at point-of-care|journal=Biosensors and Bioelectronics|volume=75|pages=254\u2013272|doi=10.1016/j.bios.2015.08.040|pmid=26319169|pmc=4601610|issn=0956-5663}}</ref>, and they may also have utility in diagnosing [[SARS-CoV-2]] ([[COVID-19]]) infections.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=Zhengtu|last2=Yi|first2=Yongxiang|last3=Luo|first3=Xiaomei|last4=Xiong|first4=Nian|last5=Liu|first5=Yang|last6=Li|first6=Shaoqiang|last7=Sun|first7=Ruilin|last8=Wang|first8=Yanqun|last9=Hu|first9=Bicheng|last10=Chen|first10=Wei|last11=Zhang|first11=Yongchen|date=2020-02-27|title=Development and Clinical Application of A Rapid IgM-IgG Combined Antibody Test for SARS-CoV-2 Infection Diagnosis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32104917|journal=Journal of Medical Virology|doi=10.1002/jmv.25727|issn=1096-9071|pmid=32104917}}</ref><ref>Humanity tested. Nat Biomed Eng (2020). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41551-020-0553-6</ref>\n\nLateral flow tests are based on a series of capillary beds, such as pieces of porous paper,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.khufash.com/bd/applications/lateral_flow/lf_main_page.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728025400/http://www.khufash.com/bd/applications/lateral_flow/lf_main_page.htm |archivedate=2012-07-28 }}</ref> microstructured polymer,<ref name=\"Synthetic microfluidic paper\">{{cite journal |author1=Jonas Hansson |author2=Hiroki Yasuga |author3=Tommy Haraldsson |author4=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2016 | title = Synthetic microfluidic paper: high surface area and high porosity polymer micropillar arrays | journal = Lab on a Chip |volume= 16 |issue=2 |pages= 298\u2013304 |doi=10.1039/C5LC01318F|pmid=26646057 |url=http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:kth:diva-180009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Synthetic paper\">{{cite journal |author1=Weijin Guo |author2=Jonas Hansson |author3=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2016 | title = Viscosity Independent Paper Microfluidic Imbibition | url = https://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1048748/FULLTEXT01.pdf| journal = MicroTAS 2016, Dublin, Ireland}}</ref> or sintered polymer.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.porex.com/products/clinical-sciences/in-vitro-diagnostics/ | title=Sample Collection & Transport &#124; Sample Preparation &#124; Sample Analysis}}</ref> Each of these pads has the capacity to transport fluid (e.g., urine, blood, saliva) spontaneously. \n\nThe sample pad acts as a sponge and holds an excess of sample fluid. Once soaked, the fluid flows to the second conjugate pad in which the manufacturer has stored freeze dried bio-active particles called conjugates (see below) in a salt-sugar matrix. The conjugate pad contains all the reagents required for an optimized chemical reaction between the target molecule (e.g., an antigen) and its chemical partner (e.g., antibody) that has been immobilized on the particle's surface. This marks target particles as they pass through the pad and continue across to the test and control lines. The test line shows a signal, often a color as in pregnancy tests. The control line contains affinity ligands which show whether the sample has flowed through and the bio-molecules in the conjugate pad are active. After passing these reaction zones, the fluid enters the final porous material, the wick, that simply acts as a waste container.\n\nLateral flow tests can operate as either [[competitive assay|competitive]] or [[sandwich assay]]s.\n\n== Colored particles ==\nIn principle, any colored particle can be used, however latex (blue color) or nanometer sized particles<ref name=\"Quesada-Gonz\u00e1lez, D. 2015\">{{cite journal |last1=Quesada-Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=Daniel |last2=Merko\u00e7i |first2=Arben |year=2015 |title=Nanoparticle-based lateral flow biosensors |journal=Biosensors & Bioelectronics |volume=15 |issue=special |pages=47\u201363 |doi=10.1016/j.bios.2015.05.050|pmid=26043315 |hdl=10261/131760 |url=http://ddd.uab.cat/record/200195 }}</ref> of [[colloidal gold|gold]] (red color) are most commonly used. The gold particles are red in color due to localized [[surface plasmon resonance]]. Fluorescent<ref>[http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/07/07/010.html (Point-of-Care Technologies) Developing rapid mobile POC systems - Part 1: Devices and applications for lateral-flow immunodiagnostics (IVDT archive, Jul 07)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> or magnetic<ref>[http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/02/04/001.html Paramagnetic-particle detection in lateral-flow assays (IVDT archive, Apr 02)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/08/07/008.html |title=Magnetic immunoassays: A new paradigm in POCT (IVDT archive, Jul/Aug 2008)<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2008-10-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028183523/http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/08/07/008.html |archive-date=2013-10-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> labelled particles can also be used, however these require the use of an electronic reader to assess the test result.\n\n== Sandwich assays ==\nSandwich assays are generally used for larger analytes because they tend to have multiple binding sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nanocomposix.com/pages/introduction-to-lateral-flow-rapid-test-diagnostics|title=Introduction to Lateral Flow Rapid Test Diagnostics|last=nanoComposix|website=nanoComposix|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> As the sample migrates through the assay it first encounters a conjugate, which is an antibody specific to the target analyte labelled with a visual tag, usually colloidal gold. The antibodies bind to the target analyte within the sample and migrate together until they reach the test line. The test line also contains immobilized antibodies specific to the target analyte, which bind to the migrated analyte bound conjugate molecules. The test line then presents a visual change due to the concentrated visual tag, hence confirming the presence of the target molecules. The majority of sandwich assays also have a control line which will appear whether or not the target analyte is present to ensure proper function of the lateral flow pad.\n\nThe rapid, low-cost sandwich-based assay is commonly used for home pregnancy tests which detect human chorionic gonadotropin, hCG, in the urine of pregnant women.\n\n[[File:ELISA or Lateral flow formats.svg|Illustrating the difference between sandwich assay and competitive assay formats of lateral flow tests]]\n<br />\n\n== Competitive assays ==\nCompetitive assays are generally used for smaller analytes since smaller analytes have fewer binding sites<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nanocomposix.com/pages/introduction-to-lateral-flow-rapid-test-diagnostics|title=Introduction to Lateral Flow Rapid Test Diagnostics|last=nanoComposix|website=nanoComposix|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>. The sample first encounters the target analyte labelled with a visual tag (colored particles). The test line contains antibodies to the target analyte. Unbound analyte will block the binding of these molecules, meaning that a visual marker will show. This differs from sandwich assays in that no band means the analyte is present. \n\n== Quantitative tests ==\nMost tests are intended to operate on a purely qualitative basis. However it is possible to measure the intensity of the test line to determine the quantity of analyte in the sample. Handheld diagnostic devices known as lateral flow readers are used by several companies to provide a fully quantitative assay result. By utilizing unique wavelengths of light for illumination in conjunction with either [[Complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor|CMOS]] or [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] detection technology, a signal rich image can be produced of the actual test lines. Using image processing algorithms specifically designed for a particular test type and medium, line intensities can then be correlated with analyte concentrations. One such handheld lateral flow device platform is made by Detekt Biomedical L.L.C..<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://idetekt.com/|title=Detekt Biomedical L.L.C.- Lateral Flow Readers for Rapid Test Strip Detection and Immunoassays|website=idetekt.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref> Alternative non-optical techniques are also able to report quantitative assays results. One such example is a [[magnetic immunoassay]] (MIA) in the lateral flow test form also allows for getting a quantified result. Reducing variations in the capillary pumping of the sample fluid is another approach to move from qualitative to quantitative results. Recent work has, for example, demonstrated capillary pumping with a constant flow rate independent from the liquid viscosity and surface energy.<ref name=\"Synthetic paper\"></ref><ref name=\"viscosity independent pump\">{{cite journal |author1=Weijin Guo |author2=Jonas Hansson |author3=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2016 | title = Capillary Pumping Independent of Liquid Sample Viscosity | journal = Langmuir |volume= 32 |issue= 48 |pages= 12650\u201312655 |doi=10.1021/acs.langmuir.6b03488|pmid=27798835 }}</ref><ref name=\"liquid properties independent pump 1\">{{cite book |author1=Weijin Guo |author2=Jonas Hansson |author3=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2017 | title = Capillary pumping with a constant flow rate independent of the liquid sample viscosity and surface energy | journal = IEEE MEMS 2017, las Vegas, USA|pages=339\u2013341 |doi=10.1109/MEMSYS.2017.7863410|isbn=978-1-5090-5078-9 |url=http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:kth:diva-196738 }}</ref><ref name=\"liquid properties independent pump 2\">{{cite journal |author1=Weijin Guo |author2=Jonas Hansson |author3=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2018 | title = Capillary pumping independent of the liquid surface energy and viscosity | journal = Microsystems & Nanoengineering |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=2 |doi=10.1038/s41378-018-0002-9|pmid=31057892 |pmc=6220164 |bibcode=2018MicNa...4....2G}}</ref>\n\nMobile phones have demonstrated to have a strong potential for the quantification in lateral flow assays, not only by using the camera of the device, but also the light sensor or the energy supplied by the mobile phone battery.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2017-06-15|title=Mobile phone-based biosensing: An emerging \"diagnostic and communication\" technology|journal=Biosensors and Bioelectronics|language=en|volume=92|pages=549\u2013562|doi=10.1016/j.bios.2016.10.062|pmid=27836593|issn=0956-5663|last1=Quesada-Gonz\u00e1lez|first1=Daniel|last2=Merko\u00e7i|first2=Arben|hdl=10261/160220|url=http://ddd.uab.cat/record/194894}}</ref> \n\n== Control line ==\nWhile not strictly necessary, most tests will incorporate a second line which contains an antibody that picks up free latex/gold in order to confirm the test has operated correctly.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Speed and simplicity ==\nTime to obtain the test result is a key driver for these products. Tests can take as little as a few minutes to develop. Generally there is a trade off between time and sensitivity \u2013 so more sensitive tests may take longer to develop. The other key advantage of this format of test compared to other immunoassays is the simplicity of the test \u2013 typically requiring little or no sample or reagent preparation.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Patents ==\nThis is a highly competitive area and a number of people claim patents in the field, most notably [[Alere]] (formerly Inverness Medical Innovations, now owned by [[Abbott Laboratories|Abbott]]) who own patents<ref>U.S. Patent No. 6,485,982</ref> originally filed by [[Unipath]]. A group of competitors are challenging the validity of the patents.<ref>[http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/00/11/002.html (News) Grassroots Web group challenging lateral-flow patents (IVDT archive, Nov 00)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> A number of other companies also hold patents in this arena.\n\n== Applications ==\nLateral flow assays have a wide array of applications and can test a variety of samples like urine, blood, saliva, sweat, serum, and other fluids. They are currently used by clinical laboratories, hospitals, and physicians for quick and accurate tests for specific target molecules and gene expression. Other uses for lateral flow assays are food and environmental safety and veterinary medicine for chemicals such as diseases and toxins.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koczula|first=Katarzyna\u00a0M.|last2=Gallotta|first2=Andrea|date=2016-06-30|title=Lateral flow assays|journal=Essays in Biochemistry|volume=60|issue=1|pages=111\u2013120|doi=10.1042/EBC20150012|issn=0071-1365|pmc=4986465|pmid=27365041}}</ref> Lateral flow tests are also commonly used for disease identification such as ebola, but the most common lateral flow test is the home pregnancy test.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Chromatography]]\n[[Category:Immunologic tests]]\n", "text_old": "{{Context|date=October 2009}}\n[[File:Lateral Flow Assay.jpg|thumb|499x499px|A NASA illustration of a lateral flow assay.[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Lateral_Flow_Assay.jpg#filehistory]]]\n'''Lateral flow tests''',<ref>[http://www.ivdtechnology.com/article/concurrent-engineering-lateral-flow-diagnostics Concurrent Engineering for Lateral-Flow Diagnostics (IVDT archive, Nov 99)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415073429/http://www.ivdtechnology.com/article/concurrent-engineering-lateral-flow-diagnostics |date=2014-04-15 }}</ref> also known as '''lateral flow [[immunoaffinity chromatography|immunochromatographic]] assays''', are simple cellulose-based devices intended to detect the presence of a target [[Analyte|analyte]] in liquid sample without the need for specialized and costly equipment, though many lab-based applications enhance their usage by employing dedicated equipment for higher sensitivity readout.<ref name=\"Yetisen2013\">{{cite journal | author = Yetisen A. K. | year = 2013 | title = Paper-based microfluidic point-of-care diagnostic devices | journal = Lab on a Chip |volume= 13 |issue= 12 |pages= 2210\u20132251 |doi=10.1039/C3LC50169H| pmid = 23652632 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/dbe9e0546e94ccba6732679cfbe080f81e6415ca }}</ref> Lateral flow tests operate on the same principles as the enzyme-linked immunosorbent assays ([[ELISA]]). In essence, these tests run a liquid along the surface of a pad with reactive molecules that show a visual positive or negative result. Typically, these tests are used for medical diagnostics for home testing, point of care testing, or laboratory use. The home pregnancy test is a known and widely used application. These tests are simple, economic and generally show results in around 5-30 minutes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koczula|first=Katarzyna\u00a0M.|last2=Gallotta|first2=Andrea|date=2016-06-30|title=Lateral flow assays|journal=Essays in Biochemistry|volume=60|issue=1|pages=111\u2013120|doi=10.1042/EBC20150012|issn=0071-1365|pmc=4986465|pmid=27365041}}</ref> Lateral flow tests have recently seen use in diagnosing ebola<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kaushik|first=Ajeet|last2=Tiwari|first2=Sneham|last3=Dev Jayant|first3=Rahul|last4=Marty|first4=Aileen|last5=Nair|first5=Madhavan|date=2016-01-15|title=Towards detection and diagnosis of Ebola virus disease at point-of-care|journal=Biosensors and Bioelectronics|volume=75|pages=254\u2013272|doi=10.1016/j.bios.2015.08.040|pmid=26319169|pmc=4601610|issn=0956-5663}}</ref>, and they may also have utility in diagnosing [[SARS-CoV-2]] ([[COVID-19]]) infections.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=Zhengtu|last2=Yi|first2=Yongxiang|last3=Luo|first3=Xiaomei|last4=Xiong|first4=Nian|last5=Liu|first5=Yang|last6=Li|first6=Shaoqiang|last7=Sun|first7=Ruilin|last8=Wang|first8=Yanqun|last9=Hu|first9=Bicheng|last10=Chen|first10=Wei|last11=Zhang|first11=Yongchen|date=2020-02-27|title=Development and Clinical Application of A Rapid IgM-IgG Combined Antibody Test for SARS-CoV-2 Infection Diagnosis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32104917|journal=Journal of Medical Virology|doi=10.1002/jmv.25727|issn=1096-9071|pmid=32104917}}</ref><ref>Humanity tested. Nat Biomed Eng (2020). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41551-020-0553-6</ref>\n\nLateral flow tests are based on a series of capillary beds, such as pieces of porous paper,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.khufash.com/bd/applications/lateral_flow/lf_main_page.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728025400/http://www.khufash.com/bd/applications/lateral_flow/lf_main_page.htm |archivedate=2012-07-28 }}</ref> microstructured polymer,<ref name=\"Synthetic microfluidic paper\">{{cite journal |author1=Jonas Hansson |author2=Hiroki Yasuga |author3=Tommy Haraldsson |author4=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2016 | title = Synthetic microfluidic paper: high surface area and high porosity polymer micropillar arrays | journal = Lab on a Chip |volume= 16 |issue=2 |pages= 298\u2013304 |doi=10.1039/C5LC01318F|pmid=26646057 |url=http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:kth:diva-180009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Synthetic paper\">{{cite journal |author1=Weijin Guo |author2=Jonas Hansson |author3=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2016 | title = Viscosity Independent Paper Microfluidic Imbibition | url = https://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1048748/FULLTEXT01.pdf| journal = MicroTAS 2016, Dublin, Ireland}}</ref> or sintered polymer.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.porex.com/products/clinical-sciences/in-vitro-diagnostics/ | title=Sample Collection & Transport &#124; Sample Preparation &#124; Sample Analysis}}</ref> Each of these pads has the capacity to transport fluid (e.g., urine, blood, saliva) spontaneously. \n\nThe sample pad acts as a sponge and holds an excess of sample fluid. Once soaked, the fluid flows to the second conjugate pad in which the manufacturer has stored freeze dried bio-active particles called conjugates (see below) in a salt-sugar matrix. The conjugate pad contains all the reagents required for an optimized chemical reaction between the target molecule (e.g., an antigen) and its chemical partner (e.g., antibody) that has been immobilized on the particle's surface. This marks target particles as they pass through the pad and continue across to the test and control lines. The test line shows a signal, often a color as in pregnancy tests. The control line contains affinity ligands which show whether the sample has flowed through and the bio-molecules in the conjugate pad are active. After passing these reaction zones, the fluid enters the final porous material, the wick, that simply acts as a waste container.\n\nLateral flow tests can operate as either [[competitive assay|competitive]] or [[sandwich assay]]s.\n\n== Colored particles ==\nIn principle, any colored particle can be used, however latex (blue color) or nanometer sized particles<ref name=\"Quesada-Gonz\u00e1lez, D. 2015\">{{cite journal |last1=Quesada-Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=Daniel |last2=Merko\u00e7i |first2=Arben |year=2015 |title=Nanoparticle-based lateral flow biosensors |journal=Biosensors & Bioelectronics |volume=15 |issue=special |pages=47\u201363 |doi=10.1016/j.bios.2015.05.050|pmid=26043315 |hdl=10261/131760 |url=http://ddd.uab.cat/record/200195 }}</ref> of [[colloidal gold|gold]] (red color) are most commonly used. The gold particles are red in color due to localized [[surface plasmon resonance]]. Fluorescent<ref>[http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/07/07/010.html (Point-of-Care Technologies) Developing rapid mobile POC systems - Part 1: Devices and applications for lateral-flow immunodiagnostics (IVDT archive, Jul 07)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> or magnetic<ref>[http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/02/04/001.html Paramagnetic-particle detection in lateral-flow assays (IVDT archive, Apr 02)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/08/07/008.html |title=Magnetic immunoassays: A new paradigm in POCT (IVDT archive, Jul/Aug 2008)<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2008-10-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028183523/http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/08/07/008.html |archive-date=2013-10-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> labelled particles can also be used, however these require the use of an electronic reader to assess the test result.\n\n== Sandwich assays ==\nSandwich assays are generally used for larger analytes because they tend to have multiple binding sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nanocomposix.com/pages/introduction-to-lateral-flow-rapid-test-diagnostics|title=Introduction to Lateral Flow Rapid Test Diagnostics|last=nanoComposix|website=nanoComposix|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> As the sample migrates through the assay it first encounters a conjugate, which is an antibody specific to the target analyte labelled with a visual tag, usually colloidal gold. The antibodies bind to the target analyte within the sample and migrate together till they reach the test line. The test line also contains immobilized antibodies specific to the target analyte, which bind to the migrated analyte bound conjugate molecules. The test line then presents a visual change due to the concentrated visual tag, hence confirming the presence of the target molecules. The majority of sandwich assays also have a control line which will appear whether or not the target analyte is present to ensure proper function of the lateral flow pad.\n\nThe rapid, low-cost sandwich-based assay is commonly used for home pregnancy tests which detects for human chorionic gonadotropin, hCG, in the urine of pregnant women.\n\n[[File:ELISA or Lateral flow formats.svg|Illustrating the difference between sandwich assay and competitive assay formats of lateral flow tests]]\n<br />\n\n== Competitive assays ==\nCompetitive assays are generally used for smaller analytes since smaller analytes have fewer binding sites<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nanocomposix.com/pages/introduction-to-lateral-flow-rapid-test-diagnostics|title=Introduction to Lateral Flow Rapid Test Diagnostics|last=nanoComposix|website=nanoComposix|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>. The sample first encounters the target analyte labelled with a visual tag (colored particles). The test line contains antibodies to the target analyte. Unbound analyte will block the binding of these molecules, meaning that a visual marker will show. This differs from sandwich assays in that no band means the analyte is present. \n\n== Quantitative tests ==\nMost tests are intended to operate on a purely qualitative basis. However it is possible to measure the intensity of the test line to determine the quantity of analyte in the sample. Handheld diagnostic devices known as lateral flow readers are used by several companies to provide a fully quantitative assay result. By utilizing unique wavelengths of light for illumination in conjunction with either [[Complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor|CMOS]] or [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] detection technology, a signal rich image can be produced of the actual test lines. Using image processing algorithms specifically designed for a particular test type and medium, line intensities can then be correlated with analyte concentrations. One such handheld lateral flow device platform is made by Detekt Biomedical L.L.C..<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://idetekt.com/|title=Detekt Biomedical L.L.C.- Lateral Flow Readers for Rapid Test Strip Detection and Immunoassays|website=idetekt.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref> Alternative non-optical techniques are also able to report quantitative assays results. One such example is a [[magnetic immunoassay]] (MIA) in the lateral flow test form also allows for getting a quantified result. Reducing variations in the capillary pumping of the sample fluid is another approach to move from qualitative to quantitative results. Recent work has, for example, demonstrated capillary pumping with a constant flow rate independent from the liquid viscosity and surface energy.<ref name=\"Synthetic paper\"></ref><ref name=\"viscosity independent pump\">{{cite journal |author1=Weijin Guo |author2=Jonas Hansson |author3=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2016 | title = Capillary Pumping Independent of Liquid Sample Viscosity | journal = Langmuir |volume= 32 |issue= 48 |pages= 12650\u201312655 |doi=10.1021/acs.langmuir.6b03488|pmid=27798835 }}</ref><ref name=\"liquid properties independent pump 1\">{{cite book |author1=Weijin Guo |author2=Jonas Hansson |author3=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2017 | title = Capillary pumping with a constant flow rate independent of the liquid sample viscosity and surface energy | journal = IEEE MEMS 2017, las Vegas, USA|pages=339\u2013341 |doi=10.1109/MEMSYS.2017.7863410|isbn=978-1-5090-5078-9 |url=http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:kth:diva-196738 }}</ref><ref name=\"liquid properties independent pump 2\">{{cite journal |author1=Weijin Guo |author2=Jonas Hansson |author3=Wouter van der Wijngaart | year = 2018 | title = Capillary pumping independent of the liquid surface energy and viscosity | journal = Microsystems & Nanoengineering |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=2 |doi=10.1038/s41378-018-0002-9|pmid=31057892 |pmc=6220164 |bibcode=2018MicNa...4....2G}}</ref>\n\nMobile phones have demonstrated to have a strong potential for the quantification in lateral flow assays, not only by using the camera of the device, but also the light sensor or the energy supplied by the mobile phone battery.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2017-06-15|title=Mobile phone-based biosensing: An emerging \"diagnostic and communication\" technology|journal=Biosensors and Bioelectronics|language=en|volume=92|pages=549\u2013562|doi=10.1016/j.bios.2016.10.062|pmid=27836593|issn=0956-5663|last1=Quesada-Gonz\u00e1lez|first1=Daniel|last2=Merko\u00e7i|first2=Arben|hdl=10261/160220|url=http://ddd.uab.cat/record/194894}}</ref> \n\n== Control line ==\nWhile not strictly necessary, most tests will incorporate a second line which contains an antibody that picks up free latex/gold in order to confirm the test has operated correctly.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Speed and simplicity ==\nTime to obtain the test result is a key driver for these products. Tests can take as little as a few minutes to develop. Generally there is a trade off between time and sensitivity \u2013 so more sensitive tests may take longer to develop. The other key advantage of this format of test compared to other immunoassays is the simplicity of the test \u2013 typically requiring little or no sample or reagent preparation.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Patents ==\nThis is a highly competitive area and a number of people claim patents in the field, most notably [[Alere]] (formerly Inverness Medical Innovations, now owned by [[Abbott Laboratories|Abbott]]) who own patents<ref>U.S. Patent No. 6,485,982</ref> originally filed by [[Unipath]]. A group of competitors are challenging the validity of the patents.<ref>[http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/00/11/002.html (News) Grassroots Web group challenging lateral-flow patents (IVDT archive, Nov 00)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> A number of other companies also hold patents in this arena.\n\n== Applications ==\nLateral flow assays have a wide array of applications and can test a variety of samples like urine, blood, saliva, sweat, serum, and other fluids. They are currently used by clinical laboratories, hospitals, and physicians for quick and accurate tests for specific target molecules and gene expression. Other uses for lateral flow assays are food and environmental safety and veterinary medicine for chemicals such as diseases and toxins.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koczula|first=Katarzyna\u00a0M.|last2=Gallotta|first2=Andrea|date=2016-06-30|title=Lateral flow assays|journal=Essays in Biochemistry|volume=60|issue=1|pages=111\u2013120|doi=10.1042/EBC20150012|issn=0071-1365|pmc=4986465|pmid=27365041}}</ref> Lateral flow tests are also commonly used for disease identification such as ebola, but the most common lateral flow test is the home pregnancy test.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Chromatography]]\n[[Category:Immunologic tests]]\n", "name_user": "NotSambo", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_flow_test"}
{"title_page": "Gerry Teifer", "text_new": "{{Infobox person | name =Gerald Emmett Teifer | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1922|5|28}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|2004|9|20|1922|5|28}} | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer =[[Acuff-Rose Music]]<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Rockabilly\n  |year=1998 |publisher= |quote=Gerry Teifer, who was in the international licensing department at Acuff-Rose Music ... | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eSNu3sirl7cC&pg=RA4-PA277&dq=%22Gerry+Teifer%22 |isbn=0-7935-9142-2 }}</ref>| occupation =[[Music publisher (popular music)|Music publishing]] | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse =Elizabeth Edmans<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/death_notices/2007/04/20/2007-04-20_fridays_death_notices.html |location=New York |work=Daily News |title=Friday's Death Notices |date=April 20, 2007 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  | partner = | children = James, Bruce, and Gary| parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}\n\n'''Gerald Emmett Teifer''' (May 28, 1922 \u2013 September 20, 2004) was an American songwriter, music publisher, recording industry executive, and entertainer.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nVcYAAAAIAAJ&q=ASCAP+Biographical+Dictionary&dq=ASCAP+Biographical+Dictionary&pgis=1 |title=ASCAP Biographical Dictionary |accessdate=2009-05-31 |year= 1966 |publisher=[[ASCAP]] }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Muskegon, Michigan]] and moved to [[Chicago]], then in 1956 he moved to [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Gerry Teifer Prepares Act for Club Circuit |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/509236212.html?dids=509236212:509236212&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Jun+09%2C+1956&author=&pub=Chicago+Daily+Tribune&desc=Gerry+Teifer+Prepares+Act+for+Club+Circuit&pqatl=google |quote=  Gerry Teifer a Chicago boy who sings on the wing label, is moving to New York for extensive prior to going on the road for personal appearances. ... |work=[[New York Times]] |date=June 9, 1956 |accessdate=2009-05-31 }}</ref>\n\nHis professional career took him to Los Angeles, and Nashville where he influenced the lives of many in the music business. Gerry's songs were recorded by numerous artists including [[Eddy Arnold]], [[Johnnie Ray]], and [[Doris Day]].<ref name=\"aust\">{{cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.cat-vn1190581 |title=Gerry Teifer |accessdate=2009-05-31 |quote= |publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> As a songwriter his best known hits were \"A Full Time Job\" recorded by [[Eddy Arnold]] (1952),<ref name=\"Joel Whitburn's Top Country Songs 1944-2008\">[http://www.recordresearch.com/ BILLBOARD HOT COUNTRY SONGS 1944-2008]</ref> and \"I Don't Care (As Long As You Care For Me)\", a song performed regularly on the [[Liberace]] show (circa 1953).<ref name=\"teiferSONYatv\">[http://www.sonyatv.com/en-us-na/ Sony/ATV Music Publishing : Welcome<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He also co-wrote the [[New York Yankees]] theme song (under the pseudonym of Bob Bundin), which was heard on radio and early television as \"Here Come The Yankees\".<ref name=obit/>\n\nGerry was also a talented whistler, and released several singles on Epic Records including \"Poco A Poco\", \"Stop, Look And Whistle\", \"Heartaches\", and \"Blue Brazil\". As a whistler he also recorded with Chuck Sagle and his Orchestra, was on the [[Leon Redbone]] album ''Double Time'' on Warner Brothers Records, and performed on numerous commercials.\n\nDuring his career, he was the first General Manager of the CBS publishing company April/Blackwood Music,<ref name=\"jcymbal\">[[Johnny Cymbal|JOHNNY CYMBAL]]</ref> President of Metromedia Music, President of RCA Records publishing division Sunbury-Dunbar Music in New York, Vice-President of ATV Music Group in Nashville and in New York, and head of foreign licensing for Opryland Music Group in Nashville.<ref name=\"teiferATV\">[http://www.byronhillmusic.com/bio.htm Bio of songwriter [[Byron Hill]]] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120140649/http://www.byronhillmusic.com/bio.htm |date=2008-11-20 }}</ref>\n\nHe was an Army paratrooper during [[World War II]], a touring table tennis champion, and was well known among his colleagues as an excellent tennis player who regularly won music industry tournaments.<ref name=obit/>\n\nHe married Elizabeth Edmans and had 3 sons, James, Bruce and Gary. He later had 8 grandchildren, Elizabeth, Dawn, Christine, Erin, Dylan, Claire, Lydia and Linda.\n\nHe retired to Dunedin, Florida, and died at St. Mark Village, [[Palm Harbor, Florida]], on September 20, 2004, at the age of 82.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Gerald E. Teifer |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AiAMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=l1wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6799,2591518&dq=teifer |quote=He was born in Muskegon, Mich., and came here in 1986 ... |work=[[Saint Petersburg Times]] |date=September 23, 2004 |accessdate=2009-05-31 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teifer, Gerald}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Michigan]]\n[[Category:American country songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Muskegon, Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Palm Harbor, Florida]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person | name =Gerald Emmett Teifer | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1922|5|28}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|2004|9|20|1922|5|28}} | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer =[[Acuff-Rose Music]]<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Rockabilly\n  |year=1998 |publisher= |quote=Gerry Teifer, who was in the international licensing department at Acuff-Rose Music ... | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eSNu3sirl7cC&pg=RA4-PA277&dq=%22Gerry+Teifer%22 |isbn=0-7935-9142-2 }}</ref>| occupation =[[Music publisher (popular music)|Music publishing]] | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse =Elizabeth Edmans<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/death_notices/2007/04/20/2007-04-20_fridays_death_notices.html |location=New York |work=Daily News |title=Friday's Death Notices |date=April 20, 2007 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  | partner = | children = James, Bruce, and Gary| parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}\n\n'''Gerald Emmett Teifer''' (May 28, 1922 \u2013 September 20, 2004) was an American songwriter, music publisher, recording industry executive, and entertainer.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nVcYAAAAIAAJ&q=ASCAP+Biographical+Dictionary&dq=ASCAP+Biographical+Dictionary&pgis=1 |title=ASCAP Biographical Dictionary |accessdate=2009-05-31 |year= 1966 |publisher=[[ASCAP]] }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Muskegon, Michigan]] and moved to [[Chicago]], then in 1956 he moved to [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Gerry Teifer Prepares Act for Club Circuit |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/509236212.html?dids=509236212:509236212&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Jun+09%2C+1956&author=&pub=Chicago+Daily+Tribune&desc=Gerry+Teifer+Prepares+Act+for+Club+Circuit&pqatl=google |quote=  Gerry Teifer a Chicago boy who sings on the wing label, is moving to New York for extensive prior to going on the road for personal appearances. ... |work=[[New York Times]] |date=June 9, 1956 |accessdate=2009-05-31 }}</ref>\n\nHis professional career took him to Los Angeles, and Nashville where he influenced the lives of many in the music business. Gerry's songs were recorded by numerous artists including [[Eddy Arnold]], [[Johnnie Ray]], and [[Doris Day]].<ref name=\"aust\">{{cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.cat-vn1190581 |title=Gerry Teifer |accessdate=2009-05-31 |quote= |publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> As a songwriter his best known hits were \"A Full Time Job\" recorded by [[Eddy Arnold]] (1952),<ref name=\"Joel Whitburn's Top Country Songs 1944-2008\">[http://www.recordresearch.com/ BILLBOARD HOT COUNTRY SONGS 1944-2008]</ref> and \"I Don't Care (As Long As You Care For Me)\", a song performed regularly on the [[Liberace]] show (circa 1953).<ref name=\"teiferSONYatv\">[http://www.sonyatv.com/en-us-na/ Sony/ATV Music Publishing : Welcome<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He also co-wrote the [[New York Yankees]] theme song (under the pseudonym of Bob Bundin), which was heard on radio and early television as \"Here Come The Yankees\".<ref name=obit/>\n\nGerry was also a talented whistler, and released several singles on Epic Records including \"Poco A Poco\", \"Stop, Look And Whistle\", \"Heartaches\", and \"Blue Brazil\". As a whistler he also recorded with Chuck Sagle and his Orchestra, was on the [[Leon Redbone]] album ''Double Time'' on Warner Brothers Records, and performed on numerous commercials.\n\nDuring his career, he was the first General Manager of the CBS publishing company April/Blackwood Music,<ref name=\"jcymbal\">[[Johnny Cymbal|JOHNNY CYMBAL]]</ref> President of Metromedia Music, President of RCA Records publishing division Sunbury-Dunbar Music in New York, Vice-President of ATV Music Group in Nashville and in New York, and head of foreign licensing for Opryland Music Group in Nashville.<ref name=\"teiferATV\">[http://www.byronhillmusic.com/bio.htm Bio of songwriter [[Byron Hill]]] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120140649/http://www.byronhillmusic.com/bio.htm |date=2008-11-20 }}</ref>\n\nHe was an Army paratrooper during [[World War II]], a touring table tennis champion, and was well known among his colleagues as an excellent tennis player who regularly won music industry tournaments.<ref name=obit/>\n\nHe married Elizabeth Edmans and had 3 sons, James, Bruce and Gary. He later had 8 grandchildren, Elizabeth, Dawn, Christine, Erin, Dylan, Claire, Lydia and Linda.\n\nHe retired to Dunedin, Florida, and died at St. Mark Village, [[Palm Harbor, Florida]], on September 20, 2004, at the age of 82.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Gerald E. Teifer |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AiAMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=l1wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6799,2591518&dq=teifer |quote=He was born in Muskegon, Mich., and came here in 1986 ... |work=[[Saint Petersburg Times]] |date=September 23, 2004 |accessdate=2009-05-31 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teifer, Gerald}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Michigan]]\n[[Category:American country songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Muskegon, Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Palm Harbor, Florida]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerry_Teifer"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States Senate election in Kentucky", "text_new": "{{For|related races|2020 United States Senate elections}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|Election to elect a United States Senator from Kentucky in 2020}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 United States Senate election in Kentucky\n| country            = Kentucky\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2014 United States Senate election in Kentucky\n| previous_year      = 2014\n| next_election      = 2026 United States Senate election in Kentucky\n| next_year          = 2026\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n| image1             =\n| nominee1           =\n| party1             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      =\n| percentage1        =\n| image2             =\n| nominee2           =\n| party2             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      =\n| percentage2        =\n| map_image          =\n| map_size           =\n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. Senator\n| before_election    = [[Mitch McConnell]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     =\n| after_party        =\n}}\n{{ElectionsKY}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States Senate election in Kentucky''' will be held on November 3, 2020, to elect a member of the [[United States Senate]] to represent the [[Kentucky|Commonwealth of Kentucky]], concurrently with the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], as well as [[2020 United States Senate elections|other elections]] to the U.S. Senate and [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections|elections]] to the [[United States House of Representatives]] and various [[2020 United States elections|state and local elections]].\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n* Nicholas Alsager<ref name=\"wdrb\"/> \n* Wendell K. Crow, businessman and entrepreneur<ref name=\"wdrb\">https://www.wdrb.com/news/senate-majority-leader-mitch-mcconnell-just-got-two-more-primary/article_18e3efd2-2201-11ea-b2fc-a74f0ffbe713.html</ref>\n* Paul John Frangedakis, chiropractor<ref name=\"wdrb\"/>\n* Louis Grider, truck driver<ref name=\"wdrb\"/>\n* Neren James<ref name=\"wdrb\"/>\n* Kenneth Lowndes<ref name=\"wdrb\"/>\n* [[Mitch McConnell]], incumbent U.S. Senator<ref>[http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article213094359.html/ Mitch McConnell to Kentucky Gov. Bevin: Stay home and run for re-election]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/1c57404aaea9427fba5478dd61f5a801|title=McConnell announces re-elect campaign at Fancy Farm picnic|work=Associated Press|first=Adam|last=Beam|date=August 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Wesley Morgan (politician)|Wesley Morgan]], former state representative<ref name=\"Morgan\">{{cite news |last1=Brammer |first1=Jack |title=Former Kentucky lawmaker challenging Mitch McConnell in GOP primary for U.S. Senate |url=https://www.kentucky.com/news/politics-government/article230935263.html |accessdate=May 31, 2019 |work=Lexington Herald Leader |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Mitch McConnell\n| list =\n;Federal officials\n* [[Donald Trump]], 45th President of the United States<ref>{{cite tweet|user=realDonaldTrump|number=1148747083219984384|title=Democrats are coming after our great Kentucky Senator, Mitch McConnell, with someone who compared my election to September 11th....|date = July 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=realDonaldTrump|number=1148747084167831553|title=....Why would Kentucky ever think of giving up the most powerful position in Congress, the Senate Majority Leader, for a freshman Senator with little power in what will hopefully be the minority party. We need Mitch in the Senate to Keep America Great!!|date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n;State officials\n* [[Matt Bevin]], 62nd Governor of Kentucky (2015-2019)<ref>{{cite tw