ggie Joe Hilliard\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Andrew Maynard\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Amy McGrath]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Eric Rothmuller\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = John R. Sharpensteen\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Bennie J. Smith\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Mary Ann Tobin]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes =\n| percentage = 100.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Libertarian primary==\nThe Libertarian Party of Kentucky does not qualify to nominate through the taxpayer-funded primary and will hold its privately-operated primary, open to those who are and remain registered to vote as a Libertarian from January 1st to present in the state of Kentucky<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lpky.org/kb/convention-participation-guidelines/|title=Libertarian Nomination participation criteria}}</ref>, on March 8th, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lpky.org/event/2020-lp-kentucky-annual-convention-2020-03-07/|title=Libertarian Party of Kentucky 2020 Annual Convention}}</ref> All candidates of the Libertarian Party of Kentucky must defeat None Of The Above (NOTA) to obtain the nomination. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lpky.org/about/governance/|title=Libertarian Party of Kentucky governance documents}}</ref>\n\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n* Brad Barron, Farmer and Entrepreneur<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bradbarron2020.com/|title=Brad Barron Campaign Website}}</ref>\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Libertarian primary results\n}}\n{{Election box  candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Brad Barron\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box  candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = None Of The Above\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes =\n| percentage = 100.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Independent Candidates==\n\n==General election==\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Source\n! Ranking\n! As of\n|-\n| align=left | [[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{cite web | title=2020 Senate Race Ratings| url=https://cookpolitical.com/ratings/senate-race-ratings |website=The Cook Political Report | accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#f99\" |{{sort|098|Likely R}}\n| March 20, 2020\n|-\n| align=left | [[Stuart Rothenberg|Inside Elections]]<ref>{{cite web | title=2020 Senate Ratings | url=https://www.insideelections.com/ratings/senate | work=Senate Ratings | publisher=The Rothenberg Political Report | accessdate=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#f66\" |{{sort|098|Safe R}}\n| March 9, 2020\n|-\n| align=left | [[Sabato's Crystal Ball]]<ref>{{cite web | title=2020 Senate race ratings | url=http://crystalball.centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2020-senate/ | website=Sabato's Crystal Ball | accessdate=August 28, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#f99\" |{{sort|098|Likely R}}\n| March 9, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Politico]]<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.politico.com/2020-election/race-forecasts-and-predictions/senate/ |title=2020 Election Forecast|date=November 19, 2019 |publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#f99\" |{{sort|103|Likely R}}\n| March 13, 2020\n|}\n\n===Polling===\n\n;with Amy McGrath\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size{{efn|Key:<br>A \u2013 all adults<br>RV \u2013 registered voters<br>LV \u2013 likely voters<br>V \u2013 unclear}}\n! Margin<br>of error\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Mitch<br>McConnell (R)\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Amy<br>McGrath (D)\n! Undecided\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Change Research <ref name=\"fivethirtyeight\">{{Cite web|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/kentucky/|title=Kentucky Polls|website=fivethirtyeight.com}}</ref>\n| Jan 17-21, 2020\n| 1281\n| \u00b1&nbsp;2.8%\n| '''41%'''\n| '''41%'''\n| 11%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Garin-Hart-Yang <ref name=\"fivethirtyeight\"/>\n| Jan 8-13, 2020\n| 802\n| \u00b1&nbsp;3.5%\n| {{party shading/Republican}}| '''43%'''\n| 40%\n| 12%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.aarp.org/content/dam/aarp/research/surveys_statistics/politics/2019/five-state-prescription-drug-survey-annotated-questionnaire-KY.doi.10.26419-2Fres.00335.003.pdf Fabrizio Ward/AARP]\n| July 29\u201331, 2019\n| 600\n| \u00b1&nbsp;4.0%\n| {{party shading/Republican}}| '''47%'''\n| 46%\n| 5%\n|}\n\n{{collapse top|1=<span style=\"font-size:88%;\">Hypothetical polling</span>|left=yes|bg=#B0CEFF;line-height:135%;|border=none}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size{{efn|Key:<br>A \u2013 all adults<br>RV \u2013 registered voters<br>LV \u2013 likely voters<br>V \u2013 unclear}}\n! Margin<br>of error\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Mitch<br>McConnell (R)\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Generic<br>Democrat\n! Undecided\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://ditchmitchfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/KentuckyMemoFeb21.pdf Public Policy Polling (D)]{{efn-ua|Poll sponsored by The Ditch Mitch Fund|name=\"TMDF\